💡 Key Concepts Learned
What is a Bare Repository?

A bare repository contains only the Git version history and metadata.

It has:

No working directory
No checked-out files
Used as a central repository for collaboration

Example:

/opt/blog.git
What is a Working Repository?

A cloned repository contains:

Project files
Working directory
Git history
Local branches

Developers edit files here before committing and pushing changes.

Example:

/usr/src/kodekloudrepos/blog
Why Clone Instead of Copy?

Using Git Clone:

Preserves commit history
Configures remote origin automatically
Maintains Git metadata
Enables collaboration

Copying files manually would lose all Git tracking information.

Real-World DevOps Scenario

Imagine your company hosts a central Git repository on an internal Git server.

Git Server
│
├── payment-api.git
├── frontend.git
├── inventory.git
└── blog.git

When a new developer joins the team, they don't receive a ZIP file of the project.

Instead, they run:

git clone git@company.com:blog.git

This creates their own working copy while the central repository remains untouched.

This is exactly what happened in today's lab.

Commands Used
su - natasha

cd /usr/src/kodekloudrepos

git clone /opt/blog.git

cd blog

git status
